WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.200
My quarantine fad of choice this last summer was gardening. Among other things, I was working

00:00:12.200 --> 00:00:17.719
with some basil, and a friend of mine sent me a recipe for pesto. Turns out that they're

00:00:17.719 --> 00:00:23.440
one of those good at cooking types, so instead of talking tablespoons or cups, this recipe

00:00:23.440 --> 00:00:29.200
was all in grams. Seeing that I don't own a scale, I realized that I had stumbled upon

00:00:29.200 --> 00:00:35.279
a totally real-world, definitely not contrived need for machine learning. I know how tall

00:00:35.279 --> 00:00:40.900
the plants are, what species they are, and some other yada yada about the concentration

00:00:40.900 --> 00:00:48.139
of some sort of chemical, and I need to estimate my basil mass. Thankfully, the previous tenant

00:00:48.139 --> 00:00:52.799
of 10 years has been collecting measurements on this same plot, so I have some solid data

00:00:52.799 --> 00:00:58.439
to work with. So what's our strategy? Maybe there's no need for anything fancy. We could

00:00:58.439 --> 00:01:03.680
start out with a linear regression. Or maybe I'm the kind of feller that uses k-n-n in

00:01:03.680 --> 00:01:08.959
the regression setting. We could run with that. Or maybe I'm feeling trendy and decide

00:01:08.959 --> 00:01:16.400
that my best move is a neural network. Or... Okay, hear me out. What if I could figure

00:01:16.400 --> 00:01:22.379
out some way to combine those outputs? I want to come up with some sort of model that generates

00:01:22.379 --> 00:01:28.360
predictions that are informed by each of these constituent models. This is the premise behind

00:01:28.360 --> 00:01:33.000
ensembling. Ensembling is a machine learning technique that has been shown to increase

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:38.360
predictive performance in a variety of settings. In a community survey conducted over the summer

00:01:38.360 --> 00:01:42.879
by the TidyModels team, we learned that users felt that the number one priority for future

00:01:42.879 --> 00:01:49.000
development in this ecosystem should be ensembling. This December, we are delighted to announce

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:54.959
the initial release of Stacks, a package for TidyModels-aligned model ensembling. When

00:01:54.959 --> 00:01:59.080
you're coding up an ensemble with Stacks, most of the code you'll end up writing isn't

00:01:59.080 --> 00:02:03.440
specific to Stacks at all. I'll skip over the code that generates these models, but

00:02:03.440 --> 00:02:08.039
the gist is that I've created three model specifications here using functionality from

00:02:08.039 --> 00:02:15.800
the TidyModels core. Packages like parsnip, workflows, recipes, and tune. The linear regression

00:02:15.800 --> 00:02:21.759
spec here just defines one model definition. There aren't any hyperparameters to tune.

00:02:21.759 --> 00:02:27.160
For this KNN model spec, though, I'm tuning over several possible numbers of neighbors,

00:02:27.160 --> 00:02:33.119
so this spec actually defines four model definitions. Finally, for this neural network model, I'm

00:02:33.119 --> 00:02:38.119
tuning over six combinations of numbers of hidden layers and dropout rates, so this spec

00:02:38.119 --> 00:02:43.600
defines six model definitions. In Stacks, each of these eleven model definitions are

00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:48.820
called candidate members, or candidates for short. These candidates are the building blocks

00:02:48.860 --> 00:02:54.500
for an ensemble. The first step to putting together a model stack is the Stacks initialization

00:02:54.500 --> 00:03:00.419
function, which works kind of like the ggplot function from ggplot2. It lays the foundation

00:03:00.419 --> 00:03:06.940
called a data stack for the model to be built on top of. Now, the first core verb in Stacks

00:03:06.940 --> 00:03:13.899
is add candidates. It takes in a candidate and adds it. We can iteratively call the function

00:03:13.899 --> 00:03:19.339
as many times as we need to to add all of the candidates. Under the hood, add candidates

00:03:19.339 --> 00:03:24.020
collects predictions on a subset of the training data from each candidate and appends them

00:03:24.020 --> 00:03:30.699
as columns to the data stack. The second core verb is blend predictions, which fits a regularized

00:03:30.699 --> 00:03:35.740
linear model on the data stack, predicting the true outcome using the predictions from

00:03:35.740 --> 00:03:40.660
each of the candidate members. We call the coefficients of this linear model stacking

00:03:40.660 --> 00:03:45.899
coefficients. A stacking coefficient of zero means that the predictions for the relevant

00:03:45.899 --> 00:03:51.660
candidate will not ultimately influence the model stack's predictions. Candidate members

00:03:51.660 --> 00:03:56.419
with non-zero stacking coefficients earn the title of members, and we can fit them on the

00:03:56.419 --> 00:04:02.580
whole training data using the fitMembers function. And that's it. The output of fitMembers is

00:04:02.580 --> 00:04:07.380
ready to predict on new data. Fingers crossed that I'll nail this pesto recipe.

00:04:10.660 --> 00:04:13.860
